Covid-19 Analysis: Afghanistan

This blog contains an analysis on the no. of cases and deaths in the year 2021 for Afghanistan and a comparison of these numbers with the time in the first half and the second half of the year i.e. before and during the on-going crises in Afghanistan.

Contents

  • Introduction
  • Data Description
  • Analysis
  • References

Introduction

Afghanistan is a country located in the south-central Asia. The country has been under a continuous conflict for 40 years and is again at war in 2021 itself. Before this it has been struggling with drought, hunger and along with it, the coronavirus disease (COVID-19) as well (Ghai, 2021).

Below, the analysis is focused on the COVID-19 numbers (cases and deaths) and its relation with the on-going crises.

Data Description

Data Source

The data set used in this blog has been extracted from World Health Organization-WHO. Which was in-turn collected by WHO via different sources. Till 21 March’20, WHO collected these numbers via official ministries of health websites, social media and through official communications under the International Health Regulations-IHR, 2005. From 22 March’20, WHO collected data through WHO dashboards and counts declared at the WHO headquarters regularly (WHO Coronavirus (COVID-19) Dashboard, 2021).

Variable description

The data set contains the data from January’20 to December’21. The variables used in the analysis are given below with their description and variable type:

Variables Description Type
Country Country - Afghanistan character
New_cases New COVID-19 cases, calculated by subtracting ‘previous total cases before the date’ from ‘current total cases till date’ numeric
Cumulative_cases Total COVID-19 cases till date numeric
New_deaths New COVID-19 deaths, calculated by subtracting ‘previous total deaths before the date’ from ‘current total deaths till date’ numeric
Cumulative_deaths Total COVID-19 deaths till date numeric
Year Year of reporting to WHO numeric
Month Month of reporting to WHO numeric

Data Information Display

Analysis Communicaion

TO <- Afghan_data %>% 
  group_by(Month) %>% 
  summarise(
            Sum_deaths = sum(New_deaths),
            Sum_cases = sum(New_cases),
            Deaths = spk_chr(New_deaths, type = "bar")) %>% 
 datatable(escape = FALSE,
            options = list(fnDrawCallback = htmlwidgets::JS('function(){HTMLWidgets.staticRender();}'))) %>% 
  spk_add_deps()

TT <- Afghan_data %>% 
  group_by(Month) %>% 
  summarise(New_cases = sum(New_cases),
            New_deaths = sum(New_deaths)) %>% 
  filter(Month %in% c("5","6","7","8")) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>%
  formattable(list(area(col = 2:3) ~ color_tile("#F5B7B1", "#7DCEA0")))
